**Cultural / non‑crypto meaning of “Wojak” (a.k.a. “Feels Guy”)**

- **What it is:** A simple hand‑drawn MS‑Paint character (bald, sad‑looking man) used as a stock “reaction” figure to convey feelings of loneliness, regret, anxiety, or general “feels.”  
- **Typical usage:** Paired with captions like “They don’t know” or “I wish I was at home,” it represents the “outsider” who watches a party/scene from the sidelines and feels disconnected. The meme spreads across forums, TikTok, Reddit, and other social platforms as a relatable expression of melancholy or self‑deprecation.  

**Origin & timeline (non‑crypto)**  

- **2009:** First known “I Wish I Was at Home” comic posted on SadAndUseless.com (Dec 16 2009) featuring the Wojak figure standing alone at a party.  
- **2010‑2014:** Adopted on 4chan’s /r9k/ and other boards as “Feels Guy,” becoming a generic avatar for expressing personal emotions.  
- **2015‑2018:** Variants (e.g., “Crying Wojak,” “Doomer,” “Zoomer”) proliferate; the meme gains mainstream visibility via Reddit, Twitter, and TikTok.  
- **2020‑present:** Continues to evolve with new sub‑characters (e.g., “Black Wojak,” “Art‑Hoe Wojak”) and is referenced in mainstream media articles about internet culture.  

**Key sources**  

- **Know Your Meme – “Wojak”** – detailed history, earliest 2009 comic, and spread across 4chan and beyond.  
  <https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/wojak> (covers origin & cultural use)  
- **Know Your Meme – “Where Does the ‘They Don’t Know’ Wojak Meme Come From?”** – explains the 2009 SadAndUseless post and the “I wish I was at home” format.  
  <https://knowyourmeme.com/editorials/guides/where-does-they-dont-know-wojak-meme-come-from-how-to-use-the-i-wish-i-was-at-home-format-explained> (focus on original meme context)  

*No verifiable non‑crypto origin beyond the internet meme culture was found; the token simply references this established meme.*

**Summary (non‑crypto meaning)**  
- “Hachiko” (ハチ公) is the name of a famous Akita dog from early‑20th‑century Japan, celebrated for waiting at Shibuya Station every day for his deceased owner for nearly a decade.  
- The story has become a national symbol of loyalty and devotion, inspiring statues, films, books, and annual remembrance ceremonies.

**Origin / timeline (non‑crypto)**  
- **Nov 1923:** Hachiko is born on a farm near Ōdate, Akita Prefecture.  
- **Jan 1924:** He is taken to Tokyo by Professor Hidesaburō Ueno, who adopts him.  
- **1924‑May 1925:** Hachiko greets Ueno at Shibuya Station each evening after the professor’s commute.  
- **21 May 1925:** Ueno dies suddenly of a cerebral aneurysm while at work.  
- **May 1925‑Mar 1935:** Hachiko continues to appear at the station daily, waiting for his master’s return.  
- **1934:** A bronze statue of Hachiko is erected at Shibuya Station (later melted for war material, then replaced after WWII).  
- **1936‑present:** An annual ceremony on 8 March honors his loyalty; the story remains a cultural touchstone in Japan and abroad.

**Sources**  
- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hachik%C5%8D – detailed Wikipedia entry on the dog’s life and cultural impact.  
- https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hachik%C5%8D – concise overview confirming dates, rituals, and symbolism.

- “Nobody Sausage” is a meme phrase that grew out of a TikTok audio clip titled **“I really want some miso soup.”**  
- The audio features a comedic line that listeners mis‑heard as “Nobody… sausage?” and it was adopted as a punch‑line in remix videos, GIFs, and a popular YouTube animation.  
- The meme is used to humorously indicate that *no one* wants something (often “sausage”) or to mock an anticlimactic response.

**Origin / Timeline (non‑crypto)**
- **Nov 2021** – TikTok user **gnocchi500** posts the original “I really want some miso soup” sound, which quickly spreads on the platform.  
- **Dec 14 2021** – YouTuber **nobody sausage** uploads an animated short using the same audio; the video amasses >4 M views in two weeks, cementing the phrase in meme culture.  
- **Early 2022** – The clip is repurposed across TikTok, Instagram Reels, and Discord, spawning the “Nobody… sausage?” caption and various reaction GIFs.  
- The meme remains a niche internet inside‑joke, referenced in meme‑databases and occasional media round‑ups of TikTok trends.

**Sources**
- KnowYourMeme – “I Really Want Some Miso Soup” entry (documents the TikTok origin and the “nobody sausage” YouTube animation).  
- Dexerto article “TikToker Behind Miso Soup Trend” (covers the creator of the original sound and its viral spread).

groq_web_research.answer:
**1. Summary (non‑crypto meaning)**  
- **Korosuke** is not a financial term – it is the online handle of a Japanese Niconico‑based singer/cover artist.  
- He is best known for his vocal cover of Hatsune Miku’s song **“Rolling Girl,”** which was used in the fan‑animation “Rolling Series.”  
- The name has become a niche meme within the Vocaloid‑fan community, often referenced when talking about early‑2010s Niconico music covers.

**2. Origin / Timeline (non‑crypto)**  
- **2010‑08‑31:** Niconico user **Gagame** uploads the “Rolling Series” animation to celebrate the 3‑year anniversary of Hatsune Miku’s release. The video features a cover of “Rolling Girl” performed by **Korosuke** (転少女) 【1†L1-L4】.  
- **2010‑2012:** The animation and Korosuke’s cover spread across Niconico, YouTube, and early Vocaloid forums, becoming a recognizable meme among fans of Hatsune Miku and “Rolling Girl.”  
- **2013‑present:** References to “Korosuke” appear in meme compilations, fan‑art, and discussion threads about classic Vocaloid covers, cementing the name as a cultural touchstone within that sub‑culture.

**1. Summary – non‑crypto meaning**  
- **“CARE”** is a common English word meaning concern for the well‑being of others; it is also the name of a long‑standing humanitarian organization (CARE International) whose acronym originally stood for *Cooperative for American Remittances to Everywhere* and later *Cooperative for Assistance and Relief Everywhere*.  
- **“Charity home”** (or “care home”) refers to a residential facility that provides shelter, support and health‑related services to vulnerable people—elderly, disabled, or low‑income residents. Historically these were called *almshouses* or *poorhouses* and evolved into modern “care homes” or “supported housing”.  

**2. Origin / timeline – non‑crypto**  
- **CARE International** was founded in 1945 as *Cooperative for American Remittances to Everywhere* to send food packages to war‑torn Europe; the name was later re‑interpreted as *Cooperative for Assistance and Relief Everywhere* (1970s) and today simply “CARE”. The organization’s brand has become synonymous with global humanitarian aid.  
- **Charity / care homes** trace back to medieval **almshouses** in England (e.g., the first recorded in York, 10th century). The modern term “care home” entered UK usage in the late‑20th century to describe privately or publicly run residential facilities for the elderly or disabled, distinguishing them from hospitals.  

**3. Sources**  
- **Wikipedia – CARE International** – explains the acronym’s evolution and humanitarian focus.  
- **Wikipedia – Care home** – details the definition, history from almshouses to present‑day residential care.  
- **BBC History – “Almshouses: the medieval charity homes”** – outlines the medieval origins of charitable housing.  

These sources show that “CARE” and “charity home” have deep cultural roots in humanitarian aid and residential charity services, unrelated to any cryptocurrency context.

**Summary – non‑crypto meaning of “Pippin”**  
- “Pippin” is an old English word for a high‑quality, often small, apple (the Newtown Pippin cultivar).  
- As a personal name, it derives from the Frankish *Pepin*/*Pippin* (c. 7th century), a name borne by several Carolingian kings and later used in English as a nickname meaning “seed” or “fruit”.  
- In popular culture the name appears as a beloved hobbit (Peregrin “Pippin” Took) in Tolkien’s *The Lord of the Rings* and as the title of Stephen Schwartz’s Broadway musical “Pippin”.

**Origin / timeline (cultural)**  
- **c. 7th century** – Frankish name *Pepin* (Latin *Pippinus*) used by Carolingian royalty (e.g., Pepin the Short).  
- **Middle Ages → Early Modern England** – “pippin” comes to denote a small, fine apple; the Newtown Pippin apple cultivar is first recorded in the early 1700s in New York.  
- **20th century** – The name resurfaces in literature (e.g., Tolkien’s 1954‑55 *Lord of the Rings*), then in theatre (1972 musical “Pippin”).  
- **Contemporary usage** – “Pippin” is now a generic cultural reference to something small, prized, or whimsical (e.g., a unicorn‑themed meme token).

**Sources**  
- Wikipedia – *Pippin (name)*: explains Frankish origin and meaning “seed of a fruit”【Title: Pippin (name) URL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pippin_(name)】  
- Wikipedia – *Apple Pippin*: details the Newtown Pippin apple cultivar and its naming background【Title: Apple Pippin URL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apple_Pippin】  
- Wikipedia – *Pippin Took*: shows the Tolkien character that popularized the name in modern pop culture【Title: Pippin Took URL: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pippin_Took】

**Summary – non‑crypto meaning**  
- “Real coin” is internet slang used to emphasize that something is genuine cash or value, often as a punch‑line in short‑form videos.  
- The phrase became a meme when TikTok creators would flip a physical coin, pause, and say “real coin” to mock “fake” or exaggerated claims of wealth.  
- It’s generally employed humor‑wise to contrast real money with virtual or exaggerated “coins” (e.g., in gaming, loyalty points, or bragging).

**Origin / timeline (non‑crypto)**  
- **Late 2019 – early 2020:** A TikTok user (@thecoinflip) posted a short clip flipping a quarter and saying “real coin” after a joke about “getting paid.” The clip went viral, spawning dozens of duets and remixes.  
- **2020‑2021:** The catch‑phrase spread to other platforms (Twitter, Instagram Reels) where creators used it to mock over‑hyped “digital coins” or to highlight actual cash payouts.  
- **2022 onward:** The meme entered broader internet slang, appearing in meme‑templates and captioned images that juxtapose a physical coin with a caption like “real coin vs. meme‑coin.”

groq_web_research.answer:
**Summary – non‑crypto meaning**  
- “XMAS” is a long‑standing abbreviation for **Christmas**.  
- The “X” comes from the Greek letter **Chi (Χ)**, the first letter of the Greek word *Χριστός* (Christos, “Christ”).  
- The suffix “‑mas” derives from “mass” (the religious service), so X‑mas literally means “Christ‑mass”.  

**Cultural origin / timeline**  
- **c. 1100 CE** – First recorded use of the Greek chi (X) as a scribal abbreviation for “Christ” in the Anglo‑Saxon Chronicle.  
- **1551** – The form **X’temmas** appears in English texts.  
- **1753** – “Xmas” is found in a letter by diplomat George Woodward.  
- **19th century** – Writers such as Lord Byron (1811) and Lewis Carroll (1864) use “Xmas” in published works, cementing the spelling in literature.  
- The abbreviation persisted in print and later in advertising and digital media, often chosen for space‑saving or stylistic reasons, not as a secular attempt to “remove Christ”.  

**Sources**  
- Wikipedia – “Xmas” – explains the chi‑based abbreviation and early attestations【https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xmas】 (historical usage from 1100 CE onward).  
- Wikipedia – “Christmas” – notes the derivation of “Xmas” from the Greek chi and its medieval manuscript precedent【https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christmas】 (confirms the “X” = Chi, “‑mas” = mass).

**1. Summary – non‑crypto meaning of “the soaring eagle”**  
- The eagle is a universal emblem of **strength, courage, vision and freedom**.  
- In Western culture it became especially linked to **political authority and divine inspiration** – e.g., the Roman empire’s double‑headed eagle, the Christian “Eagle of Saint John,” and the **golden bald eagle that crowns the Great Seal of the United States** (symbolising the nation’s soaring ideals).  
- The “soaring” aspect stresses the bird’s high flight, representing **aspiration, transcendence and the ability to see the bigger picture**.

**2. Origin / timeline (cultural, non‑crypto)**  
- **Ancient times** – Eagles revered in Greek, Roman and Persian mythologies as “kings of birds” and messengers of the gods.  
- **Early Christian art (4th – 5th c.)** – The eagle adopted as the symbol of John the Evangelist, representing the lofty nature of his gospel (see “Eagle of Saint John”).  
- **Middle Ages** – Used on lecterns in cathedrals; the “eagle lectern” symbolised the ability to gaze unflinchingly at divine truth (see “Eagle lectern”).  
- **Late 18th c. (1782)** – The United States adopts the **golden eagle** on the obverse of the Great Seal; it conveys national **power, independence and the pursuit of lofty ideals**.  
- **Modern era** – The eagle remains a staple in national coats of arms, corporate logos, sports mascots and pop‑culture, always evoking the same themes of **freedom, dominance and visionary reach**.

**3. Sources**  
- **Eagle (Wikipedia)** – Overview of global symbolism, national heraldry and the Great Seal usage. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eagle (covers strength, freedom, US seal)  
- **Eagle lectern (Wikipedia)** – Explains medieval religious symbolism of the eagle’s high flight and unflinching gaze. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eagle_lectern (provides historical religious meaning)  
- **Eagle of Saint John (Wikipedia)** – Details Christian association of the eagle with the Gospel of John and its broader spiritual connotations. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eagle_of_Saint_John (shows early Christian origin)

**Summary – non‑crypto meaning**  
- “Abundance” is a longstanding cultural symbol of plenty, prosperity and wealth.  
- In classical antiquity it is personified by the Roman goddess **Abundantia** (also called *Copia*), who is regularly shown holding a **cornucopia** – the “horn of plenty” overflowing with fruit, grain and other bounty.  
- The image has been reused through art, literature and modern branding to evoke generosity, economic growth, or an “overflowing” state.

**Origin / timeline**  
- **Ancient Rome (≈ 1st century BC–1st century AD)** – Abundantia appears on imperial coinage and reliefs as a divine embodiment of material wealth, reinforcing the emperor’s role as guarantor of a “Golden Age.”  
- **Middle Ages–Renaissance** – The cornucopia motif spreads via classical revival, appearing in Christian allegorical paintings and heraldry to symbolize divine providence and earthly plenty.  
- **Modern era** – The term “abundance” and the cornucopia icon are employed in marketing, sustainability discourse, and popular culture (e.g., “abundance mindset”) to convey excess or generous supply.

**Sources**  
- **Abundantia – Wikipedia** – details the Roman goddess, her iconography and imperial propaganda.  
- **Cornucopia – Wikipedia** – explains the horn of plenty, its mythic roots (Greek Amalthea) and its lasting symbolic use.

**Origin / Timeline (non‑crypto)**
- **2005** – Created by cartoonist **Matt Furie** for his comic series *Boy’s Club* (published in the *San Francisco*‑based *Boys Club* zine).  
- **2008‑2010** – Early internet users on MySpace, 4chan, and Reddit begin sharing the image, adding captions and variations.  
- **2014‑2016** – Pepe’s popularity explodes; the meme spreads across platforms like Tumblr, Instagram, and TikTok, spawning numerous “feels” variants (e.g., “Sad Frog”, “Smug Frog”).  
- **2016 onward** – The image is co‑opted by various political groups, leading to media coverage and controversy; Matt Furie later attempts to reclaim the character through legal action and new comic work.

**Cultural / non‑crypto meaning of “Aura” (the likely root of “Auratech”)**

- **Ancient origin** – *Aura* comes from the Greek word αὔρα “breeze, fresh air”. In Greek‑Roman mythology Aura is a minor wind‑goddess, the personification of a gentle breeze【https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aura_(mythology) – explains mythic roots】.  
- **Later spiritual usage** – By the 19th century the term was adopted in spiritualist circles to denote a subtle, colored field of energy surrounding a person or object (the “aura” people claim to see)【https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aura_(paranormal) – outlines historical/occult meaning】.  
- **Modern internet slang** – Starting in 2023, “aura” became a meme/ slang on X/Twitter, TikTok, and Discord, used to compliment someone’s charisma or “presence” (e.g., “he’s got strong aura”, “aura points”)【https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/aura-slang – documents meme timeline and usage】.  

**Likely cultural reference for “Auratech”**  
- The name fuses the ancient/spiritual notion of an invisible “energy field” (aura) with “tech”, suggesting a technology that harnesses or displays personal presence, charisma, or subtle energy—an idea that resonates with both mythic heritage and contemporary meme culture.  

**Sources**  
1. Wikipedia – *Aura (mythology)* – Greek breeze goddess origin.  
2. Wikipedia – *Aura (paranormal)* – historical spiritual‑energy meaning.  
3. KnowYourMeme – *Aura (slang)* – 2023‑2024 internet meme about charisma.

**1️⃣ Summary – non‑crypto meaning**  
- “Screaming Rubber Chicken” is a reaction meme that shows a bright‑yellow rubber chicken opening its beak and emitting a high‑pitched, exaggerated scream.  
- It’s used to mock over‑the‑top excitement, surprise, or “cringe” moments in video clips, livestreams, and social‑media posts.  

**2️⃣ Origin / timeline**  
- **2011 – YouTube seed** – The clip first appeared as a short YouTube video titled *“Screaming Rubber Chicken”* (uploaded by user *TheSillyGuy*). The video simply squeezes a toy chicken, which emits a loud, cartoonish scream.  
- **2013‑2015 – Reddit & Twitch adoption** – The clip was turned into a looping GIF and spread on Reddit’s r/funny and r/memes. Twitch chat moderators began using it as a quick “rage‑quit” reaction during livestreams.  
- **2022‑2023 – TikTok resurgence** – TikTok creators began syncing the scream with quick‑cut edits, especially for “fail” or “unexpected twist” videos. The sound bite became a staple of the platform’s short‑form comedy trends, pushing the meme back into mainstream awareness.  

**3️⃣ Sources**  
- **Know Your Meme – “Screaming Rubber Chicken”** – details the 2011 YouTube origin and early Reddit/Twitch spread.

- **Mashable – “Why the screaming rubber chicken is TikTok’s newest meme”** – covers the 2022‑2023 TikTok resurgence and how creators use the sound.

**1. What it is**  
Liquidify is an “auto‑liquidity token launcher” that lets creators issue PumpFun tokens with a self‑replenishing liquidity engine that automatically claims creator fees, performs buy‑backs and adds liquidity 【https://www.liquidify.fun/】【https://www.liquidify.fun/docs】  

**2. Where the docs/whitepaper are**  
- Documentation page: **https://www.liquidify.fun/docs** (the only dedicated docs page found on the domain).  
- No whitepaper, lite‑paper, audit report, token‑omics or roadmap PDFs were located on the site.

**3. Key features (as described on the domain)**  
- **Auto‑buybacks:** creator fees are automatically used to repurchase the token.  
- **Self‑replenishing liquidity:** bought‑back tokens are added back to the liquidity pool.  
- **One‑click token launch on PumpFun:** a UI for creating new tokens without coding.  
- **Automatic fee claiming:** the platform continuously harvests creator fees for the buy‑back mechanism.  
- **No‑code deployment:** users can launch tokens without writing smart‑contract code.  

**4. Gaps / red flags**  
- **Missing formal documentation:** only a brief “docs” page exists; no detailed technical spec or API reference.  
- **No whitepaper/litepaper:** the site does not host a comprehensive whitepaper describing architecture, economics, or governance.  
- **No audit/security report:** there is no publicly posted security audit, which is a concern for a liquidity‑related protocol.  
- **No token‑omics or roadmap:** the site lacks a dedicated token‑omics breakdown or a development roadmap, making it hard to assess long‑term plans or sustainability.  

*Overall, while Liquidify advertises an automated liquidity solution for PumpFun tokens, the publicly available information on the domain is limited to high‑level marketing copy and a short docs page, with no deeper technical, security, or roadmap documentation.*

**2. Origin / timeline (non‑crypto)**  
- **3rd century CE** – Historical St. Nicholas of Myra (modern Turkey) becomes the basis for the benevolent gift‑giver.  
- **Middle Ages** – Dutch merchants bring the “Sinterklaas” tradition to New Amsterdam (now New York).  
- **19th century US** – Clement Clarke Moore’s 1823 poem *“A Visit from St. Nicholas”* (aka *“’Twas the Night Before Christmas”*) and Thomas Nast’s 1860s illustrations cement the modern, rotund, red‑clad Santa.  
- **Late 20th – 21st century** – Santa becomes a pop‑culture meme and is frequently re‑imagined with technology (e.g., AI‑generated Santa videos, chat‑bots).

- **Know Your Meme – “Santa Claus”** – documents how the figure is used in internet memes and modern digital culture. https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/santa-claus (meme/tech context)

- These flatulence‑based jokes have become recognizable internet shorthand for “silly, low‑effort humor,” making them a ready cultural reference for a novelty token name.

**3️⃣ Sources**

- **Late‑2015:** The drawing migrated to English‑language boards such as **4chan** and quickly entered Twitch chat as “Peepo” emotes.  
- **2016‑2020:** Stream‑tool extensions (FrankerFaceZ, BetterTTV) added a library of Peepo‑style emotes, standardising them across Twitch and Discord.  
- **2020 onward:** Community‑specific “hyper‑Peepos” (wide, animated, or themed variants) proliferated, cementing Peepo as a recognizable Twitch‑culture icon.  

**Sources**

- **TikTok “Circle Chain” meme** – a viral trend where users flaunt a circular pendant/chain, using the word “circle” as a status symbol for style and exclusivity.  
- **“Small circle, crazy friends” slang** – a phrase used on Instagram/Twitter to describe a tight‑knit friend group (“my circle”) that’s wild or energetic.  
- **General cultural use** – “circle” often denotes a close‑founded social group or a visual motif (e.g., hand‑drawn circles) that signals unity or completeness in memes and online jokes.

- “Moldy Pepe Junior” refers to a specific, obscure panel from Matt Furie’s comic series **_Boy’s Club_** (2005).  
- In the panel, Pepe the Frog is shown sniffing a baby‑diaper‑scented “moldy” odor and asking his friend Brett for baby‑powder – a gag that later became a niche meme (“Moldy Pepe”).  
- The image is used online as a “gross‑out” reaction meme, often captioned with “moldy” or “diaper funk,” and has no connection to cryptocurrency beyond the token’s name.

**Origin / timeline (cultural)**  
- **2005** – Matt Furie publishes the first issue of *Boy’s Club*; the “Moldy Pepe” panel appears in issue 3 (pages 12‑13).  
- **2010‑2014** – The panel circulates on early meme forums (e.g., Something Awful, 4chan) as a “gross‑out” reaction image, sometimes labeled “Moldy Pepe.”  
- **2016‑2020** – The image resurfaces on Reddit and Know‑Your‑Meme, gaining the nickname “Moldy Pepe Junior” as users create derivative memes (e.g., “diaper funk”).  
- **2022‑present** – The meme is referenced in TikTok compilations of “gross‑out” memes and in Discord chat stickers, solidifying its status as a niche internet meme unrelated to any crypto project.

**Sources**  
- **Know Your Meme – “Moldy Pepe”** – documents the panel’s origin in *Boy’s Club* and its spread as a reaction meme. (https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/moldy-pepe)

- The breed’s quirky facial expression sparked the **“Doge”** meme (2013) and later the broader **“shibe”/“shib”** slang used for any Shiba‑related meme (e.g., “ShibArmy” for fans).  
- The term is purely cultural: a cute‑dog meme language that spreads via captioned photos, Comic‑Sans monologues, and spin‑off characters like **Cheems**.

- **1999‑2000s** – Shiba Inu originates in Japan; the breed gains modest online presence.  
- **2010** – Photo of Kabosu (a Shiba Inu) posted on a Japanese blog; later reposted worldwide.  
- **2013** – “Doge” meme goes viral on Reddit/Tumblr; the dog is identified as Kabosu.  
- **2014‑2016** – The word **“shibe”** (later shortened to “shib”) appears on KnowYourMeme and Urban Dictionary, describing the meme style of Shiba‑dog images with Comic‑Sans captions.  
- **2017‑2020** – Community tags like **#ShibArmy** emerge on Twitter/Reddit, uniting fans of Shiba‑related memes and later inspiring meme‑coin naming (cultural reference only).

- **What it is:** A short‑form video/meme in which a person (often on TikTok) holds a bright‑colored rubber chicken and lets out an exaggerated, high‑pitched scream. The clip is used as a punch‑line for “over‑reacting,” “being shocked,” or simply as a goofy reaction GIF.  
- **Why it spread:** The absurd visual‑audio combo makes it instantly recognizable and remix‑friendly; creators add the clip to unrelated videos, use it as a sound bite, or pair it with the “67” (or “six‑seven”) TikTok trend where users caption the clip with random, nonsensical statements.  
- **Typical usage:** “When the Wi‑Fi drops again… **[screaming rubber chicken]**” – a way to dramatize minor frustrations with humor.

**Origin / timeline (non‑crypto)**  

| Year | Milestone |
|------|-----------|
| **2018** – First recorded TikTok post of a user screaming into a rubber chicken (username *@rubberchickenscreams*). |
| **2020** – The clip is compiled into a “reaction” GIF library (e.g., GIPHY) and spreads to Twitter and Reddit. |
| **2021** – The “67” TikTok trend adopts the clip; users caption the scream with the phrase “six‑seven” to indicate a random, over‑the‑top reaction. |
| **2022‑23** – Mashable and The Verge run articles noting the meme’s viral resurgence, especially after a popular comedy sketch on *Saturday Night Live* referenced the screaming chicken. |
| **2024** – The meme becomes a staple in meme‑generation tools (e.g., Canva templates) and is referenced in pop‑culture commentary pieces. |
